    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Dual-Class Stock Structure in SpaceX\'s IPO\n\n## Classes of Common Stock\n\nBased on the prospectus excerpts, SpaceX has **four classes of common stock** authorized, all with par value of $0.001 per share:\n\n| Class | Authorized Shares | Voting Rights | Outstanding Post-IPO |\n|-------|------------------|---------------|---------------------|\n| **Class A** | 36,132,150,000 | 1 vote per share | Being offered in IPO |\n| **Class B** | 6,125,000,000 | 10 votes per share | Outstanding (concentrated ownership) |\n| **Class C** | 10,000,000,000 | No voting rights | None issued/outstanding |\n| **Class D** | (authorized) | To be established when issued | None issued/outstanding |\n\nAdditionally, **2,400,000,000 shares of preferred stock** are authorized but none are outstanding.\n\n## Voting Rights Per Share\n\n- **Class A**: One vote per share\n- **Class B**: Ten votes per share\n- **Class C**: No voting rights (except as required by law)\n- **Class D**: Voting rights to be established by the Board if/when issued\n\n## Allocation of Voting Power\n\n### General Voting (Single Class)\nClass A and Class B shareholders **vote together as a single class** on all matters submitted to shareholders, except where Class B has special class voting rights.\n\n### Board Election (Split Voting)\n- **Class B shareholders**, voting separately as a class, elect **51% of the total authorized directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number)—these are the "Class B Directors"\n- **Class A and Class B together**, voting as a single class, elect the remaining directors—the "Common Stock Directors"\n\n### Special Class B Protective Provisions\nClass B shareholders, voting separately as a class, have exclusive approval rights over:\n\n1. **Removal of Elon Musk** from his board and leadership roles (CEO and Chairman)\n2. **Removal of Class B Directors** (with or without cause)\n3. **Filling vacancies** among Class B Directors\n4. **Charter amendments** affecting Class B rights, powers, preferences, or privileges\n5. **Certain combinations, mergers, or sales** as described in the charter\n\n### Conversion Mechanics\n- Each Class B share is **convertible at holder\'s option** into one Class A share at any time\n- **Automatic conversion** of Class B to Class A occurs upon any transfer (whether or not for value), except for "Permitted Transfers" (certain inter-family transfers and transfers to qualifying entities)\n- This mechanism means that over time, as Class B shares are sold/transferred, they convert to lower-vote Class A, **increasing the relative voting power** of remaining Class B holders\n\n## Concentration of Control\n\nThe structure is designed to consolidate control with Elon Musk:\n\n- Musk beneficially owns **approximately 93.6% of Class B common stock** (pre-offering)\n- This translates to **approximately 85.1% of combined voting power** (pre-offering)\n- Post-IPO, Musk will hold a **majority of the voting power** of common stock\n- As a result, Musk can:\n  - Elect **all members of the board** (Class B Directors through Class B ownership; Common Stock Directors through combined voting power)\n  - Control the outcome of **all matters requiring shareholder approval**\n  - Only be removed from his CEO/Chairman positions by a **Class B shareholder vote**\n\n## "Controlled Company" Status\n\nDue to this concentration, SpaceX will qualify as a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules, allowing it to rely on exemptions from certain corporate governance requirements, including:\n- Not requiring a majority of independent directors on the board\n- Not requiring independent compensation and nominating committees\n\nHowever, the company remains subject to the requirement for an **audit committee composed entirely of independent directors**.\n\n## Anti-Takeover Considerations\n\nThe dual-class structure, combined with Texas anti-takeover statutes (Section 21.606 of the TBOC), creates significant barriers to unsolicited acquisitions or changes in control, as public Class A shareholders have **limited or precluded ability** to influence corporate matters or board elections.',
