    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Controlled-Company Status and Governance Exemptions\n\n## Basis for Controlled-Company Status\n\nUnder the listing rules of **Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas**, a company of which more than 50% of the voting power with respect to director elections is held by another person or group of persons acting together is a "controlled company." Following the IPO, Elon Musk will beneficially own shares of Class A and Class B common stock representing **greater than 50% of the voting power** of the company\'s common stock with respect to director elections. Additionally, under the charter, holders of Class B common stock (voting separately as a class) are entitled to elect **51% of the total number of authorized directors** (rounded up to the nearest whole number). Because Mr. Musk will hold a majority of the Class B common stock, he will control the election of the Class B Directors and, for so long as he holds a majority of the combined voting power, the remainder of the board as well.\n\n---\n\n## Specific Nasdaq / Nasdaq Texas Listing Rules the Company Is Exempt From\n\nAs a controlled company, SpaceX may elect **not to comply** with the following Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements:\n\n| # | Exempted Requirement |\n|---|---|\n| 1 | **Majority-independent board** — A majority of the company\'s board of directors must consist of independent directors as defined under the listing rules. |\n| 2 | **Independent nominating committee** — Director nominees must be selected or recommended for the board\'s selection by a nominating committee composed **entirely of independent directors**, with a written charter addressing the nominations process. |\n| 3 | **Independent compensation committee** — The compensation committee must be composed **entirely of independent directors**, with a written charter addressing the committee\'s purpose and responsibilities. |\n| 4 | **Annual committee performance evaluations** — Annual performance evaluations of the compensation and nominating committees must be conducted. |\n\n> **Note:** The text references only **Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas** listing rules — not NYSE. The company has applied to list its Class A common stock on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas under the symbol **"SPCX."**\n\n### What Remains Required\n\nThe company explicitly states that, even as a controlled company, it **remains subject to the rule requiring an audit committee composed entirely of independent directors.** This requirement is **not** exempted.\n\n---\n\n## Board Composition Requirement (and How the Company Will Operate Without It)\n\n### The Exempted Standard\n\nThe standard Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas requirement from which the company is exempt is that **a majority of the board of directors consist of independent directors.** A controlled company need not meet this threshold.\n\n### Actual Post-IPO Board Composition\n\nThe company\'s board will consist of **eight directors**, divided into two categories under the charter:\n\n| Director Class | Elected By | Initial Members |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Class B Directors** (51% of authorized directors, rounded up) | Class B common stock, voting separately as a class | Elon Musk, Gwynne Shotwell, Antonio J. Gracias, Donald Harrison, Luke Nosek |\n| **Common Stock Directors** (remaining members) | Class A and Class B common stock, voting together as a single class | Ira Ehrenpreis, Randy Glein, Steve Jurvetson |\n\nThe board is subject to **annual elections**, with each director holding office until the next annual meeting and until a successor is duly elected and qualified, or until earlier death, resignation, or removal.\n\n### Independence Determinations\n\nThe board has determined that **five of the eight directors** are independent within the meaning of Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing standards:\n\n- Ira Ehrenpreis\n- Randy Glein\n- Donald Harrison\n- Steve Jurvetson\n- Luke Nosek\n\nThis means **five of eight** directors (a majority) are independent — though the company is not *required* to maintain this majority so long as it remains a controlled company.\n\n---\n\n## Committee Structure Under the Exemptions\n\n### Compensation and Nominating Committee\n\n- **Expected members:** Ira Ehrenpreis (chair), Antonio J. Gracias, and Luke Nosek.\n- The company **will rely on the controlled-company exemption** from the requirement that this committee be composed entirely of independent directors with a charter addressing all applicable Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas requirements.\n- Ira Ehrenpreis and Luke Nosek each qualify as independent (including heightened independence standards for compensation committee members) and as "non-employee directors" under Rule 16b-3. Antonio J. Gracias\'s independence status is not affirmatively stated in the excerpt.\n- The committee\'s responsibilities include overseeing compensation philosophy, reviewing/approving executive compensation, recommending director candidates, and performing other board-assigned functions.\n\n### Audit Committee\n\n- **Expected members:** Randy Glein (chair) and Steve Jurvetson, with a third member to be identified within the applicable one-year transition period under Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas rules.\n- Randy Glein is expected to qualify as an "audit committee financial expert" under SEC rules implementing Section 407 of Sarbanes-Oxley.\n- Both qualify as independent for purposes of Rule 10A-3 of the Exchange Act and Nasdaq/Nasdaq Texas listing standards.\n- The audit committee is **not exempt** from independence requirements.\n\n---\n\n## Historical Compensation Practices\n\nDuring the last completed fiscal year, the company was not publicly traded and had no compensation committee. The **full board** determined and made all decisions regarding Mr. Musk\'s compensation. For other executive officers, **Mr. Musk had primary responsibility** for compensation-related decisions, though all equity awards were approved by the board.\n\n---\n\n## Shareholder Protection Warning\n\nThe company expressly warns that, as a result of utilizing these exemptions, **Class A shareholders will not have the same protections** afforded to shareholders of companies subject to all Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas corporate governance requirements. The company may elect to take advantage of certain other exemptions in the future for as long as it remains a "controlled company."\n\nIf the company **ceases to be a controlled company** while its shares remain listed on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas, it will be required to comply with all applicable governance requirements within the applicable transition periods.',
