        output='# Class B Common Stock Conversion Mechanics\n\n## 1. Voluntary Conversion (Holder Option)\n\nEach share of Class B common stock is **convertible at any time at the option of the holder** into **one share** of Class A common stock, on a **1:1 ratio**. This is a unilateral right of the holder and requires no corporate action or approval.\n\n## 2. Automatic Conversion Upon Transfer\n\nThe primary automatic conversion trigger is a **"Transfer"** of the Class B share. The charter defines "Transfer" broadly to include:\n\n> "any sale, assignment, encumbrance, transfer, conveyance, hypothecation, pledge, gift, or other transfer or disposition of any kind of such share of Class B common stock or any legal or beneficial interest in such share, **whether or not for value** and **whether voluntary or involuntary or by operation of law**, including, without limitation, the transfer of, or entering into a binding agreement with respect to, **voting control over such share by proxy or otherwise**."\n\nKey features of this trigger:\n- It applies to **both legal and beneficial interests** in the share.\n- It captures **non-value transfers** (e.g., gifts) and **involuntary transfers** (e.g., by operation of law).\n- It expressly includes **transfers of voting control by proxy or binding agreement**, preventing holders from delegating voting power to third parties while retaining nominal ownership to preserve the 10-vote multiplier.\n- The conversion is **automatic** — it occurs by operation of the charter, not by board discretion.\n\n## 3. Permitted Transfers (Exceptions to Automatic Conversion)\n\nThe charter carves out **"Permitted Transfers"** that do **not** trigger automatic conversion. These fall into five categories:\n\n| Category | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| **(i)** | Transfers **to and from the registered holders** of Class B common stock (i.e., transfers among existing Class B holders of record). |\n| **(ii)** | Transfers by natural persons who transferred Class B shares or equity awards (including options or warrants exercisable/convertible into Class B) to certain **"permitted entities"** as defined in the charter. |\n| **(iii)** | Transfers to **family members** of shareholders described in categories (i) and (ii). |\n| **(iv)** | Transfers to certain **trusts, general partnerships, limited partnerships, LLCs, corporations, or other entities** owned by certain "qualified shareholders" (as defined in the charter), including certain permitted non-for-profits. |\n| **(v)** | Transfers to **bona fide trusts for the benefit of charitable organizations** (contributions deductible for federal income, estate, gift, and GST tax purposes), to **certain retirement accounts**, and for **certain estate or succession planning purposes**. |\n\n"Permitted Transferees" are the recipients of Class B shares in a Transfer that qualifies as a Permitted Transfer. The design of these exceptions ensures that the high-vote shares remain within a controlled circle of the original holders, their families, and their estate-planning vehicles.\n\n## 4. Impact on the Sunset of the Dual-Class Structure\n\n### No Time-Based Sunset\n\nThe charter contains **no automatic time-based sunset** provision. Unlike some dual-class structures that convert all high-vote shares to low-vote shares after a fixed number of years or upon the founder\'s death, this structure **persists indefinitely** so long as Class B shares remain outstanding and are not transferred outside the Permitted Transfer framework.\n\n### Gradual Erosion Through Transfers\n\nThe conversion-on-transfer mechanic functions as a **transfer-based sunset**:\n\n> "The conversion of Class B common stock to Class A common stock will have the effect, over time, of **increasing the relative voting power of those holders of Class B common stock who retain their shares**."\n\nThis means:\n- Each transfer of Class B shares (outside Permitted Transfers) permanently removes those shares from the high-vote class.\n- The remaining Class B holders see their **relative voting power increase** because the total number of Class B shares declines while their individual holdings remain unchanged.\n- The dual-class structure does not "sunset" in the conventional sense; rather, it **concentrates** over time into fewer hands.\n\n### Control Concentration Risk\n\nThe prospectus explicitly warns of a control-shift risk:\n\n> "If Mr. Musk were to sell, transfer or otherwise dispose of a sufficient number of his shares of Class B common stock such that he no longer holds a majority of the outstanding shares of Class B common stock, **another holder or group of holders of Class B common stock could obtain the ability to elect and remove a majority of our board** and thereby effectively control the Company."\n\nThis is a critical structural feature: because Class B holders (voting separately as a class) elect **51% of the authorized directors** for so long as any Class B shares remain outstanding, control of the board is determined by **whoever holds a majority of the outstanding Class B shares** — not by the overall shareholder base. If Mr. Musk\'s Class B holdings fall below 50% of outstanding Class B shares (through transfers that convert to Class A), control of the board could shift to another Class B holder or coalition, even if Mr. Musk remains the largest economic shareholder.\n\n### No Separate Class Votes Under Texas Law\n\nThe charter opts out of separate class voting rights that would otherwise be required under the Texas Business Organizations Code (TBOC) — including for increases/decreases in authorized shares, exchanges, reclassifications, or cancellations — **except** for:\n1. Amendments to the charter that change the rights, powers, preferences, or privileges of Class B common stock (including Class B Director provisions); and\n2. Certain combinations, mergers, or sales described in the charter.\n\nThis opt-out further entrenches the Class B holders\' control by preventing Class A holders from using statutory class vote protections to block corporate actions.\n\n## Summary\n\n| Mechanic | Detail |\n|----------|--------|\n| **Voluntary conversion** | At holder\'s option, anytime, 1:1 into Class A |\n| **Automatic conversion trigger** | Any "Transfer" (broadly defined) of the Class B share or any legal/beneficial interest therein, whether or not for value, voluntary or involuntary |\n| **Permitted Transfers (exceptions)** | Transfers among registered Class B holders; to permitted entities; to family members; to qualified-shareholder-owned entities/trusts; to charitable trusts, retirement accounts, and estate-planning vehicles |\n| **Time-based sunset** | **None** — no automatic expiration |\n| **Transfer-based sunset** | Gradual erosion of Class B count through non-permitted transfers; remaining holders\' relative voting power increases |\n| **Board control** | Class B holders (as a class) elect 51% of directors so long as any Class B shares are outstanding; control follows majority of outstanding Class B shares |\n| **Control-shift risk** | If Mr. Musk\'s Class B holdings fall below majority of outstanding Class B, another holder/coalition could gain board control |',
