tock in this offering, to influence corporate matters and the election of our directors."*\n\n## 3. Post-IPO Voting Power Percentage\n\nThe S-1 leaves the exact post-IPO figure blank (denoted by `________%`), as the offering price and share count are not yet finalized. However, the filing repeatedly confirms:\n\n- Musk will hold **"a majority of the voting power of the common stock"** post-IPO\n- He will hold **"greater than 50% of the voting power"** with respect to director elections\n- The company will qualify as a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq rules (which requires >50% voting power held by a single person)\n\nGiven the pre-offering baseline of **85.1%** and that IPO-issued Class A shares (1 vote each) will only modestly dilute his ~56.5 billion votes, his post-IPO voting power will remain **well above 50%**, likely in the **high 70s to low 80s percent range** depending on offering size — while his economic ownership will drop below 50%.\n\nThis structural wedge means public shareholders will bear a significant share of economic risk and reward while having essentially no ability to influence board composition, executive removal, or strategic direction.',
