--|-------------|--------|\n| Class A shares owned | 849,494,440 | 12.3% of Class A |\n| Class B shares owned | 5,569,053,075 | 93.6% of Class B |\n| **Total economic ownership** | (849,494,440 + 5,569,053,075) / (6,932,508,000 + 5,602,790,410) | **~51.2%** |\n| **Combined voting power** | As reported in filing | **85.1%** |\n| **Wedge (voting − economic)** | 85.1% − 51.2% | **~33.9 percentage points** |\n\nMusk holds roughly **half the economic equity** but approximately **85% of the voting power**. Public Class A shareholders will bear a substantial share of economic risk and reward (the ~49% of equity Musk does not own) while holding essentially no ability to influence board composition, executive removal, or strategic direction.\n\nThe IPO itself **widens** this wedge: only Class A shares (1 vote each) are issued, which dilutes Musk\'s economic ownership proportionally but barely touches his voting power, because each new share adds only 1 vote against his existing ~55.7 billion Class B votes.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Conversion Mechanics and the Absence of a Time-Based Sunset\n\nThe structure has **no automatic time-based sunset**. Instead, it relies on a **transfer-based sunset**:\n\n- **Voluntary conversion:** Each Class B share is convertible at holder option into one Class A share (1:1), anytime.\n- **Automatic conversion upon "Transfer":** Any transfer (broadly defined to include sales, gifts, pledges, proxy transfers, and involuntary transfers, whether or not for value) of a Class B share — or any legal/beneficial interest therein — automatically converts it to Class A.\n- **Permitted Transfers (exceptions):** Transfers among registered Class B holders, to family members, to qualifying trusts/entities, and to certain estate-planning/charitable vehicles do **not** trigger conversion.\n\nThis means the dual-class structure **persists indefinitely** so long as Class B shares remain within the permitted circle. Over time, non-permitted transfers erode the Class B count, **increasing the relative voting power of remaining Class B holders** — the structure concentrates rather than dissipates.\n\nA critical control-shift risk is disclosed: if Musk\'s Class B holdings fall below a majority of outstanding Class B shares (through conversions), **another Class B holder or coalition could gain the ability to elect and remove a majority of the board** — even if Musk remains the largest economic shareholder. Board control follows the majority of outstanding Class B shares, not the majority of economic equity.\n\n---\n\n### 6. The Core Distinction\n\n| Dimension | Governance Control | Economic Ownership |\n|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| **Musk\'s stake** | ~85.1% voting power; elects all 8 directors; controls all shareholder matters | ~51.2% of total equity; bears ~half of economic risk/reward |\n| **Public Class A holders** | Cannot elect any director; cannot remove Musk; limited influence on charter/M&A | Bear ~49% of economic risk/reward (post-IPO, before further dilution) |\n| **Source of divergence** | 10:1 Class B voting multiplier + class-segregated board elections | 1:1 economic rights across classes |\n| **Controlled-company effect** | Exempts SpaceX from independent-board, nominating, and compensation-committee requirements | Does not alter economic rights — dividends, liquidation, and conversion rights remain equal across classes |\n| **Sunset** | No time-based sunset; transfer-based erosion only; control follows majority of outstanding Class B | Economic ownership unaffected by class; only diluted by new share issuance |\n\n**The key analytical point:** Controlled-company status is a **governance** concept — it relaxes board-independence and committee-independence requirements — but it does **not** alter **economic** rights. Class A and Class B shares carry identical economic entitlements (dividends, liquidation, 1:1 conversion). The wedge between Musk\'s ~51% economic ownership and ~85% voting power 